### Step 1 — Search: find a recent parent paper

Rationale: The closest parent among the candidates is the 2019 MaveDB paper, because it provides infrastructure for multiplexed assays of variant effect, which can be extended toward a base-editing-enabled saturation missense fitness platform.

```action
{
  "tool": "search",
  "query": "multiplexed assays of variant effect MaveDB variant effect fitness missense DNA repair gene base editing screening",
  "year_min": 2018,
  "year_max": 2025,
  "k": 5
}
```

[result]

Selected parent paper:

```json
{
  "paper_id": "oa:W2987965949",
  "year": 2019,
  "title": "MaveDB: an open-source platform to distribute and interpret data from multiplexed assays of variant effect",
  "rationale_for_parent_choice": "Provides a general MAVE data and interpretation framework that can be extended to a concrete high-throughput base-editing screen measuring missense variant fitness effects."
}
```

---

### Step 2 — Extract genome: extract the parent’s 6-field `gene_genome`

Rationale: Extract the methodological genome of the MaveDB parent paper as a reusable baseline: it supports distribution, standardization, and interpretation of variant-effect datasets, but does not itself define a base-editing experimental platform for a specific DNA repair gene.

```action
{
  "tool": "extract_genome",
  "paper_id": "oa:W2987965949"
}
```

[result]

```json
{
  "gene_genome": {
    "biological_system": "General multiplexed assays of variant effect across genes, proteins, organisms, and experimental systems.",
    "variant_space": "User-submitted variant libraries including substitutions, indels, and other experimentally measured sequence variants.",
    "perturbation_delivery": "Assay-agnostic; MaveDB stores and distributes datasets generated by external mutagenesis, library construction, or selection methods.",
    "assay_design": "Standardized deposition of MAVE experiments, score sets, metadata, variant annotations, and links to publications.",
    "fitness_readout": "Variant effect scores, enrichment measurements, or functional scores provided by contributing studies.",
    "data_modeling_and_resource": "Open-source database and web resource for sharing, visualizing, interpreting, and reusing MAVE data."
  }
}
```

---

### Step 3 — Propose: child `gene_genome` extending the parent

Rationale: Extend the parent from a general MAVE data platform into a concrete experimental screening platform: use base editors to install all possible missense variants in a DNA repair gene, measure cell fitness, and output standardized variant-effect maps compatible with MAVE-style dissemination.

```action
{
  "tool": "propose",
  "gene_genome": {
    "biological_system": "Human cell model carrying a base-editing-compatible endogenous DNA repair gene, such as BRCA1, MSH2, MLH1, or TP53-pathway DNA repair context.",
    "variant_space": "Saturation design targeting all possible missense variants in the chosen DNA repair gene, prioritizing editable codons across adenine and cytosine base-editor windows and including synonymous, nonsense, and splice-proximal controls.",
    "perturbation_delivery": "Pooled high-throughput base-editing platform using tiled sgRNA libraries, matched cytosine and adenine base editors, lentiviral or stable editor delivery, and deep sequencing to quantify editing outcomes per guide.",
    "assay_design": "Competitive growth and DNA-damage-challenge screens comparing untreated versus genotoxic-stress conditions, with time-course sampling and guide-to-variant deconvolution to estimate variant-specific fitness effects.",
    "fitness_readout": "Variant-level fitness scores derived from sgRNA abundance changes, edit fractions, bystander-edit correction, replicate concordance, and differential fitness under DNA repair stress.",
    "data_modeling_and_resource": "Integrated computational pipeline producing calibrated missense effect maps, uncertainty estimates, ClinVar/pathogenicity comparisons, saturation coverage reports, and MAVE-compatible public deposition."
  }
}
```

[result]

```json
{
  "proposed_child": {
    "summary": "A base-editing saturation missense fitness platform for an endogenous DNA repair gene.",
    "extension_over_parent": "Moves from general MAVE data distribution to a concrete pooled base-editing experimental and analytical workflow that generates new variant-effect data.",
    "gene_genome": {
      "biological_system": "Human cell model carrying a base-editing-compatible endogenous DNA repair gene, such as BRCA1, MSH2, MLH1, or TP53-pathway DNA repair context.",
      "variant_space": "Saturation design targeting all possible missense variants in the chosen DNA repair gene, prioritizing editable codons across adenine and cytosine base-editor windows and including synonymous, nonsense, and splice-proximal controls.",
      "perturbation_delivery": "Pooled high-throughput base-editing platform using tiled sgRNA libraries, matched cytosine and adenine base editors, lentiviral or stable editor delivery, and deep sequencing to quantify editing outcomes per guide.",
      "assay_design": "Competitive growth and DNA-damage-challenge screens comparing untreated versus genotoxic-stress conditions, with time-course sampling and guide-to-variant deconvolution to estimate variant-specific fitness effects.",
      "fitness_readout": "Variant-level fitness scores derived from sgRNA abundance changes, edit fractions, bystander-edit correction, replicate concordance, and differential fitness under DNA repair stress.",
      "data_modeling_and_resource": "Integrated computational pipeline producing calibrated missense effect maps, uncertainty estimates, ClinVar/pathogenicity comparisons, saturation coverage reports, and MAVE-compatible public deposition."
    }
  }
}
```

